    "what_description": "Lavandula angustifolia is a compact, perennial shrub native to the Mediterranean region, belonging to the family Lamiaceae. Its botanical characteristics include narrow, linear leaves that are 2-4 cm long and 0.5-1 cm wide, and purple flowers in spikes, 5-8 cm long, appearing from June to September. The plant grows to a height of 30-50 cm and a width of 25-30 cm, with a spreading habit. Its flowers are highly fragrant and contain a mixture of linalool and linalyl acetate, making them a popular source of essential oil. Lavandula angustifolia is also known as English lavender and is commonly cultivated for its ornamental and medicinal value.",
