    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Lavandula angustifolia improperly include developing skin irritation due to its high concentration of linalool and linalyl acetate, which can cause contact dermatitis and allergic reactions in some individuals. Additionally, Lavandula angustifolia may interact with medications such as blood thinners, diabetes medications, and sedatives, exacerbating their side effects and potentially leading to adverse reactions. Long-term use of Lavandula angustifolia essential oil has been linked to liver damage and toxicity in some cases, particularly when ingested or used in high concentrations. Furthermore, Lavandula angustifolia may induce seizures in individuals with a history of epilepsy or those taking anticonvulsant medications, as it can affect the nervous system and increase excitability. The FDA has also warned about the potential for allergic reactions, including anaphylaxis, in individuals with known allergies to lavender."
